# Sorting Algorithms in Java

Sorting underpins binary search, interval merging, two-pointer problems, and much more. Know each algorithm's time/space complexity, stability, and when to prefer one over another. Java's standard library uses dual-pivot Quicksort for primitives and TimSort for objects.

## Merge Sort — stable, O(n log n) guaranteed
```java
void mergeSort(int[] a, int l, int r) {
    if (l >= r) return;
    int m = l + (r - l) / 2;
    mergeSort(a, l, m);
    mergeSort(a, m + 1, r);
    merge(a, l, m, r);  // combine two sorted halves
}
// Time: O(n log n) best/avg/worst
// Space: O(n) auxiliary array
// Stable: YES
```

## Quick Sort — fast in practice, O(n²) worst case
```java
void quickSort(int[] a, int l, int r) {
    if (l >= r) return;
    int p = partition(a, l, r);  // Lomuto: pivot = a[r]
    quickSort(a, l, p - 1);
    quickSort(a, p + 1, r);
}
// Time: O(n log n) avg, O(n²) worst (sorted input + bad pivot)
// Space: O(log n) call stack avg
// Stable: NO
```

## Heap Sort — O(n log n) worst, in-place
```java
void heapSort(int[] a) {
    int n = a.length;
    // Build max-heap bottom-up
    for (int i = n/2 - 1; i >= 0; i--) heapify(a, n, i);
    // Extract max one by one
    for (int i = n - 1; i > 0; i--) {
        swap(a, 0, i);
        heapify(a, i, 0);
    }
}
// Time: O(n log n) always
// Space: O(1)
// Stable: NO
```

## Complexity comparison table
| Algorithm  | Best      | Average   | Worst     | Space    | Stable |
|------------|-----------|-----------|-----------|----------|--------|
| Bubble     | O(n)      | O(n²)     | O(n²)     | O(1)     | Yes    |
| Selection  | O(n²)     | O(n²)     | O(n²)     | O(1)     | No     |
| Insertion  | O(n)      | O(n²)     | O(n²)     | O(1)     | Yes    |
| Merge      | O(n lg n) | O(n lg n) | O(n lg n) | O(n)     | Yes    |
| Quick      | O(n lg n) | O(n lg n) | O(n²)     | O(log n) | No     |
| Heap       | O(n lg n) | O(n lg n) | O(n lg n) | O(1)     | No     |
| Counting   | O(n+k)    | O(n+k)    | O(n+k)    | O(k)     | Yes    |

## Java Arrays.sort and Comparator
```java
// Primitives → dual-pivot Quicksort (fast, NOT stable)
Arrays.sort(intArray);

// Objects → TimSort (stable, adaptive — O(n) on nearly-sorted)
Arrays.sort(strArray);

// Custom order with Comparator
Arrays.sort(people, Comparator.comparingInt(p -> p.age));
Arrays.sort(people, (a, b) -> a.name.compareTo(b.name));
```

## Common Pitfalls
- Assuming Arrays.sort is stable for int[] — it uses Quicksort (NOT stable)
- Off-by-one in Lomuto partition: pivot ends at index p, not p-1
- Not handling many duplicates in Quicksort — degrades to O(n²) without 3-way partition
- Using O(n log n) comparison sort when counting sort (O(n+k)) is applicable

## Connections
- **Arrays**: sorting is a prerequisite for binary search and interval problems
- **Recursion**: merge sort and quick sort are recursive divide-and-conquer
- **Heaps**: heap sort uses the heap data structure directly
- **Two Pointers**: after sorting, merge and Dutch-flag patterns apply naturally
